    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_217807"><font size="6">Nightprowl: Gerald's Search</font><br />
<br />
BEEP-BEEP-BEEP-BEEP sounded the travel alarm, and after a swing and a miss Gerald hit the snooze on the second attempt.  He opened his eyes and stared at the ceiling, feeling as though the hours of sleep did nothing to refresh his mind or body.  He glanced over to the empty side of the bed and in his mind's eye he saw Cathy sleeping peacefully by his side.<br />
<br />
&quot;Stupid, stupid, stupid&quot; he chastised himself. <i>'I should've asked her up.  I should've told her how I feel about her'</i> he thought to himself, second-guessing his actions hours earlier.  He could still smell her flowery perfume, taste her lips on his, and remember her warm smile in every small detail.  &quot;It's early, but I could call her now&quot; he told himself out loud. No, it was too early.  He slipped out of the bed and walked to the bathroom, walking back out twenty minutes later, shaved, showered, and feeling a bit better.  As he was exiting the bathroom he noticed a note under his door.  He picked it up and opened it; it was typed on hotel stationary and read:<br />
<br />
<b><i>Gerry,<br />
Decided to patrol last night.  Will be sleeping all morning.  Call me tonight.<br />
     C.</i></b><br />
<br />
&quot;Well, she does still have to do her job&quot; Gerald reasoned to himself, disappointed that he'd have to wait until tonight before talking with Cathy again.  Gerald went down to the hotel restaurant and ordered breakfast and read the day's newspaper, then headed off to City Hall to get ready for the day's workshop.<br />
<br />
As Gerald was walking over to City Hall when one of his students ran up to him.  It was Samantha Donner, a young but promising mutant who had succeeded in blowing out some windows the day before in an attempt to control her fire based powers.  &quot;Mr. Simms! Mr. Simms!  You should see what I can do!&quot; she gleefully announced.<br />
<br />
&quot;Hello Samantha. Maybe you could show it to me in class so all the students can see&quot; Gerald replied.<br />
<br />
&quot;Uhm... I think it'd be better if I tried it out here - I haven't quite perfected it, and... well, I don't want to break any more windows.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald chuckled &quot;Alright, let's see what you can do.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I tried this a while ago and couldn't get it right so I put it off for a bit.  With your concentration techniques I decided to try again last night and it worked, so here goes.&quot;<br />
<br />
She concentrated intensely and quickly flame appeared.  In a burst of fire a large flaming scimitar appeared in her hand and she held it up in victory. &quot;Yeah!  See, just like War Witch!&quot; she cheerfully stated<br />
<br />
Gerald applauded.  &quot;That's great Samantha. Keep up the good work and maybe someday you can show it to War Witch herself.&quot;<br />
<br />
Samantha started to blush. &quot;Really?  No, she wouldn't be interested...&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald could see the innocence on her face, and it flashed across his mind that Cathy was strong and independent yet after five months Paragon City had turned her cold and full of doubt.  He wondered what chance Samantha would have in this environment if she didn't have anyone there to support her.  &quot;Samantha,&quot; Gerald stated in his 'teacher's voice' &quot;just remember that powers do not make the hero.  It gives you an advantage, but you still have to struggle with what you see every day.  Never be afraid to ask for help.  Please, promise me that.&quot;<br />
<br />
The sudden change in Gerald's voice worried Samantha.  &quot;Um, sure Mr. Simms.  I hope you don't expect me to do any serious crime fighting soon - I'm not ready yet.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald saw the concern on Samantha's face and caught himself. &quot;I'm sorry, it's just that I have a friend who had been doubting herself for a while and she didn't tell me.  I think she's going to be okay now, but I don't want the same thing happening to you.  If you feel down and unhappy, tell somebody.  Don't bottle it up just because you think you're supposed to be stronger than everyone else.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Oh, okay&quot; she replied, put at ease by Gerald's words.  &quot;Are you leaving soon or something?  I was hoping if I had some trouble I could talk to you.&quot;<br />
<br />
An innocent comment that sparked a thought in his mind.  Could he stay longer, maybe even get transferred to Paragon City's GIFT branch?  Maybe he could become a teacher - he enjoyed it, and it made him feel good knowing he was helping mutants to control their powers. He and Cathy could be together again, maybe find out if they could make their relationship work.  &quot;I work on the west coast right now; I'm just here for a few more days.  I'll have to see though.  Maybe I can stay longer.&quot;  Gerald looked at his watch.  &quot;We have to hurry - we don't want to be late for class&quot;.<br />
<br />
Samantha laughed &quot;Silly, you're the teacher. You can't be late even if you <i>are</i> late - the class starts when you get there.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald grinned. &quot;I suppose so, but how do you know I'm not there already?&quot;  With that Gerald turned himself invisible.<br />
<br />
Samantha's eyes bulged and Gerald almost couldn't help but laugh; her expression was priceless.  &quot;Mr. Simms?  Teach?&quot;  She held out her hand to where Gerald had been standing, but he had already taken a couple steps backwards.  &quot;He can teleport!&quot;  Samantha looked at her watch; class was about to start.  She broke into a run dreading she'd be late for class and ready to proclaim the complete unfairness of the situation should she be questioned in front of the classroom.  <i>&quot;I was late because I was outside talking to you, Teach.&quot;</i>  Everyone would laugh at her.<br />
<br />
Gerald smiled at Samantha's innocence and hoped that she could hold onto it even after she started to uncover the bad side of Paragon City.  <i>'Maybe there is a place for me here'</i> he thought to himself.<br />
<br />
<br />
***2***<br />
<br />
<br />
The day's concentration exercises went even better than Gerald had hoped, and Samantha showed off her new Fire Sword to the rest of the class to a big applause.  By the afternoon most of the class had pretty good control over their powers and a couple of the students had tried new out new abilities to varying degrees of success.  It was then that a man opened the door and stepped into the classroom.  He wore all black except for a red sash.  His goatee, stringy black hair, and eypatch screamed 'ruffian' but his smile was mildly charismatic.  No doubt he knew that and used it to his advantage.<br />
<br />
Likewise the stranger gave Gerald the once-over, noting his short brown hair, pressed khaki pants, dress shirt and tie, all topped off with a sweater vest.  <i>'So this is Cathy's boyfriend.  Heh, he looks like an accountant.  I can't believe Cathy fell in love with an accountant.  And who wears a sweater vest?!  Getting a rise out of him is going to be too easy'</i> he thought to himself. &quot;You're Gerald, right?  Hi, I'm Jack Scratch, swashbuckler extraordinaire. I'm a friend of Nightprowl. Have you seen the little kitten around? I can't seem to find her so I figured she'd be hanging around with you&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Kitten?  Cathy lets you call her 'kitten'?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Well, no, but it's never stopped me before.  So, have you seen her?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I thought she was at her place.  She left me a message that said she went out for a late night patrol, so she's probably sleeping.&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack looked puzzled.  &quot;Hmm.  She didn't checked in for a patrol last night.  She was supposed to meet me a couple hours ago but didn't show.  I just figured she got lucky with you.  You know...&quot;  the pelvic thrust that followed was wholly unnecessary. Gerald's face went red with embarrassment and a chitter of snickers ran through the classroom. Jack flashed a smile at the class and winked, playing the part of a class clown who'd just nailed the teacher with a spitball.  Gerald decided right then and there that he didn't like this guy.  He was crude and obnoxious.<br />
<br />
&quot;Okay, haha, everyone gets a good laugh, now settle down&quot; Gerald addressed the class, then turned to Jack. &quot;No.  I haven't seen her since last night.&quot;  Gerald thought about it for a bit, then he got an idea of where she might be.  &quot;No, she wouldn't... she promised me..&quot; he muttered.  He looked at Jack.  &quot;Try checking with Eden's hazard door guards to see if she checked in there.  She's been trying to find a friend of hers.&quot;  <br />
<br />
Gerald looked at his watch; there was 20 minutes to go in the day's session but he felt he needed to make sure Cathy was okay, so he turned and addressed the classroom. &quot;I want everyone practicing their concentration exercises, and tonight I want everyone to read Chapter Five: Understanding Advanced Genetic Mutations. Class dismissed.&quot;  He turned back to Jack &quot;How about you go to Eden and see if anyone has seen her and I'll go to her apartment and see if she's home.&quot;<br />
<br />
They split up and while Jack checked out Eden, Gerald went to Cathy's apartment. After an uneventful walk, Gerald arrived at her apartment and pressed the buzzer - no answer.  After a second buzz and no answer Gerald began to worry.  He started buzzing apartments on the same floor hoping to get someone who could knock on Cathy's door just to make sure.  After a few attempts someone finally answered.<br />
<br />
&quot;Hello?&quot; said a woman's voice.<br />
<br />
&quot;Hi, my name is Gerald Simms.  You don't know me, but I'm worried about a friend of mine who's on your floor, Cathy Watts, she's in apartment 2204.  Would you mind knocking on her door to see if she's okay?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Sure, no problem.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Thank you very much&quot;<br />
<br />
After a couple minutes he heard the woman's voice again, and she sounded concerned.  &quot;You should come up here - her door was unlocked but I called her name and nobody answered.&quot;  The door buzzer went off, unlocking the front door.  He opened it and went up to the 22nd floor.  During the elevator ride up he had a sick feeling in his gut that something was very wrong.  As the elevator doors opened he was met by a woman with a concerned look in her eyes.  &quot;You're Gerald? I knocked and nobody answered, so I tried the doorknob - it was unlocked.  I didn't go in, but I called out for her and nobody answered.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Okay, I'll check it out.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald looked into Cathy's apartment and instantly noticed something was wrong.  The rug in her living room was gone and there were pink stains on the carpet.  He peered into the kitchen; a box of Special K and carton of milk were on the counter beside a bowl filled with the cereal.  Gerald walked into the kitchen and placed the back of his hand on the milk - it was room temperature.  He carefully walked back towards Cathy's bedroom, glancing into the den on the way and finding it undisturbed.  He peered into Cathy's bedroom and noticed her Nightprowl costume laid out on the bed, and the pit in Gerald stomach grew when he saw Cathy's lucky collar on her bedside table.  <i>'She would NEVER leave without her collar'</i> he thought to himself.  He remembered Cathy's costume had a phone in it - he reached into the suit, found the pocket with the cell phone and pulled it out, removing the wires for the earpiece and wrist microphone.  He pressed redial in hopes that he could find out who she last called.<br />
<br />
Gerald heard the voice he didn't want to hear. &quot;Hey kitten, we've been looking for you!&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Jack, it's Gerald.  It seems you're the last person she called from her costume.  Get to Cathy's apartment - I think she's been kidnapped.&quot;  Saying the words out loud hit Gerald hard.  The full weight of the situation was unbearable.  He hung up on Jack without saying another word and walked back towards the front door, finding the woman still there.  She saw the look on Gerald's face and misread it as a worst case scenario.  She put her hands up to her face and gasped.  Gerald realized what she was thinking. &quot;Oh... no, she's not here.  Go to your apartment and call the police. Tell them that a hero has been kidnapped.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald wandered back into Cathy's room, picked up her collar from the bedside table, and sat down on her bed next to her Nightprowl costume.  He stared at the collar in his hands and began going through the past day in his mind, hoping that he could remember something unusual that would help.  All he could think of was how helpless he felt.<br />
<br />
<br />
***3***<br />
<br />
<br />
Late afternoon drew into evening and the police were canvassing the area in full force.  The apartment was thoroughly searched and Gerald just sat in Cathy's room in a daze.  He nodded or shook his head at questions he forgot seconds later, and Jack just looked in on him once, not bothering with words.  Jack knew there weren't any to offer except the standard &quot;We'll find her&quot;, and &quot;Don't worry, she'll be okay&quot; , but Jack wasn't that kind of person; he knew she wasn't okay and that she may never be found, and wasn't about to lie to Gerald just to make him feel better.<br />
<br />
Gerald felt like he'd sat there for days before his mind started urging him to get up.  <i>'You're of no use to her like this.  Do something.'</i>  He raised up off the bed and walked into the living room.  The detective who introduced himself to Gerald earlier - Gerald had forgotten his name - was directing the scene.  &quot;Excuse me.&quot; he said in a weak voice.  &quot;Excuse me, I think I know who might have her.  His name is Roeper.  Samuel Roeper.&quot;<br />
<br />
The detective stared at him for a second, then responded &quot;Yes Mr. Simms.  You already told me about Samuel Roeper. Remember?  While I was talking to you in the bedroom?&quot;  Gerald nodded, though he couldn't recall the conversation.  &quot;I've just been told that he's still in prison, but that's doesn't mean he's not somehow involved.  Since Miss Watts is a mutant hero GIFT does have a right to be present when I talk to him. Will you be there on GIFT's behalf?&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald flashed back to his last 'meeting' with Samuel Roeper; Roeper was instructing one of his henchmen to fire an electrical current through Gerald's body every time he refused to answer Roeper's questions.  He involuntarily put his hand to his chest and his face went pale. &quot;No. No, I can't&quot; he replied, wondering if the detective knew what Roeper had done to him.  In an effort to change the subject Gerald asked &quot;Do you know what happened?  I mean, how she was taken?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I can't be 100% positive, but this is what I have so far&quot; the detective began.  &quot;She's making breakfast when she hears a knock on the door.  She opens the door to find a delivery man holding a dozen red roses - the roses we found in the trash.  She doesn't think anything unusual is going on until she's struck by a tranquilizer dart.  She pulls it out and throws it over there, where we eventually found it. She's still strong enough to fight back and either cuts the guy or gives him a bloody nose - those pink stains on the carpet is blood that they tried to clean up.  They wouldn't have bothered with it if it was her blood.  She's weakened by the drug and overpowered, probably by an accomplice hiding just outside the door.  Maybe another dose of the drug puts her out for good, then they roll her up in the missing rug, dump bleach on the carpet in an attempt to destroy the evidence, and take her down to a waiting vehicle.<br />
<br />
My gut says she was abducted by more than one person but I haven't completely ruled out a single attacker.  I have a man checking out the service elevator, but there's also the possibility that they simply took her down in the main elevator under the guise of moving furniture - we'll be asking tenants if they saw anyone using the main elevator to move a rug.  I don't think they'd use the stairs but I've got another man on that just in case.  Even if they had the strength and endurance to carry her down twenty two floors it would be too risky because of the time it would take.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I think there's a lobby camera&quot; Gerald replied, remembering glancing up at it the day before.  &quot;Maybe it caught whoever brought up the roses.&quot;  His mind was starting to work again - the shock of losing Cathy was wearing off and the need to find Cathy was taking over.  &quot;Maybe you should get a list of everyone who bought a dozen roses in Paragon City over the past week.  It won't help now, but it could help when you get a list of possible names.&quot;<br />
<br />
The detective knew Gerald was only trying to help, but he was starting to get in the way.  &quot;Thank you Mr. Simms, I'll check it out.  Mr. Simms, why don't you go back to your hotel?  I've got a lot of things to go over here and I assure you I want to find Miss Watts just as quickly as you do.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Yeah, okay... did I tell you about the note?  I don't remember.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;What note?&quot; the detective replied, pulling out his notepad and flipping it open.<br />
<br />
&quot;I told Cathy last night that I was going to call her in the morning, but when I woke up I had a hotel message slipped under my door which read that she went on patrol that night and she was going to be sleeping all morning, so call her in the afternoon.  It was signed 'C'.  I don't know if it's a real hotel message or if someone made a fake message and delivered it to my hotel room themselves, but it must've been made by the guys who have Cathy.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Where did you tell her you were going to call her this morning?  In a public place, or in private?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Out in front of my hotel.  The hotel doorman was there.&quot; <i>'The doorman who said I should have invited her up to my room'</i> Gerald thought to himself.  <i>'If she was with me this morning she wouldn't have been kidnapped. Stupid Gerald. Stupid, stupid, stupid.'</i><br />
<br />
&quot;Thank you Mr. Simms.  If the doorman saw someone suspicious loitering around we might have our first suspect.  I'd like to have an officer drive you back to your hotel to get that note, and to take a statement from the doorman if he's working today.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald slid his hands in his pockets, making sure cathy's collar was still safe.  &quot;Okay. I'm ready to go now if that's possible.&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
***4***<br />
<br />
<br />
The next several days were hard on Gerald.  He finished up teaching his workshop but he felt cheated; he wanted to be happy for his students but he couldn't stop thinking of Cathy; where was she?  Was she okay? Who kidnapped her?  He phoned the police station twice a day and canvassed the area around her apartment trying to find someone who had seen her.  On the third day of Cathy's disappearance he phoned his boss, asking for a leave of absence so he could stay in Paragon City and keep searching.  On the fifth afternoon since Cathy's disappearance Gerald walked into the hotel lobby and ran into the detective in charge of Cathy's case.  &quot;We need to talk, Mr. Simms&quot; he said, &quot;Let's go up to your room&quot;.  Gerald paused. The tone of the detective's voice was ominous, but there was no question that he'd listen.<br />
<br />
They approached Gerald's door and the detective noticed a 'do not disturb' sign on the doorknob.  They entered Gerald's hotel room and the detective caught the first evidence of a man under stress.  Clothes were scattered on the floor, Two pizza boxes were on the dresser, and a collection of empty beer bottles were beside the pizza.  A crease in the wall in the shape of a fist told the detective Gerald had punched it in anger.<br />
<br />
&quot;Right from the start I just want to tell you I never wanted to come here today and suggest what I'm about to ask.  The situation with your friend is dire.&quot;  Gerald didn't like how the conversation was starting.  Gerald's efforts had come up empty and he had hoped the detective had been more successful in find out anything with regards to Cathy's kidnapping.  There was evidence from the crime scene but it was useless without a suspect.  <br />
<br />
&quot;There is something going on, some political strings are being pulled - very influential strings.  Since I was put on your friend's case I've been given several new cases; I'm all of the sudden swamped with work that could have and should have gone to other detectives.  I've had requests for certain testing turned down, and the blood samples and tranquilizer dart have disappeared from our testing lab.  I'm being set up to fail your friend and I don't like it one bit.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald stared at the detective in disbelief.  Someone was trying to make sure Cathy was never found and was doing a good job at it.  Gerald gulped hard; it was bad enough that Cathy was missing, but for the person to be connected enough to be able to hamper a police investigation... the fire of hope in Gerald dwindled to an ember.<br />
<br />
&quot;There is one person who knows who has her&quot; the detective continued.  &quot;I'm convinced he knows; I saw the way he looked at me. Samuel Roeper.  I need you to interview him.  I know what he did to you and I know what your powers are, and I'm hoping that you can use your powers to get him to tell you who has her.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald knew it was inevitable.  For the past few days he was trying to find a way to find Cathy without confronting Samuel Roeper, but he couldn't escape it.  They had to meet one more time, and Cathy's life may hang in the balance.<br />
<br />
&quot;I want to talk to him alone.  Just the two of us.&quot;<br />
<br />
The detective shook his head emphatically. &quot;No. You're not doing it alone.  You need someone with you.  I read the reports of what he did to you and this isn't the time for emotions.  I'll be right beside you when you talk to him.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I don't want you there&quot; Gerald replied. Gerald knew the detective would end the interview if things got a little too intense, and Gerald knew they would.  But if he ended the interview too soon Gerald wouldn't get the name he needed - the name of the person who abducted Cathy.   &quot;He's already seen you and knows you, and if I show up as your lackey we wouldn't get anything out of him.&quot;  Gerald tried to think of someone who wouldn't get in his way during the interview; someone who believed in 'an eye for an eye'.  &quot;I'll take Cathy's friend, Jack.  Jack Scratch.  He'll provide an intimidation factor and Sam's never seen him.&quot; <br />
<br />
The detective looked at Gerald, studying his face.  Gerald did his best to appear sincere, hiding the real motivation for not wanting the detective present at Roeper's questioning.  &quot;Alright.  You and Jack Scratch.  I'll have it arranged for tomorrow morning.&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
***5***<br />
<br />
<br />
Gerald waited nervously outside the entrance to the Zigursky Correctional Facility, waiting for Jack to arrive.  Samuel Roeper had been transferred there shortly after his conviction due to his connection with the 5th column - all captured 5th column officers were housed at Zigursky. Gerald couldn't help but wonder if Roeper had been able to orchestrate Cathy's abduction from his cell; probably not, but he wouldn't discount it just yet.<br />
<br />
Gerald was deep in thought, planning how to maneuver the interview and contemplating what he'd be able to offer Roeper in trade for the name Gerald needed, when Jack put his hand on Gerald's shoulder.  &quot;Sorry I'm late&quot; he said. &quot;I needed a morning workout, so I decided to check up on a friend of mine who needed some help with a Circle of Thorns base.  It took a bit longer than I thought it would.  You wouldn't believe the twisting maze of corridors in their bases - not to mention the huge underground caverns.  Impressive indeed.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;No problem, I was just thinking&quot; Gerald replied.  &quot;You're just here to observe, okay?  I can handle myself and I don't need you interfering in my interview.&quot;  Gerald was unneedingly cold to Jack, but Jack knew he wasn't quite the same person he'd met days before; Gerald had stopped shaving, his clothes were wrinkled, and he could see the look of desperation growing in his eyes.  &quot;Just remember why you're here&quot; Jack replied.  &quot;You're here to find out who might have Cathy, you're not here for vengeance for what Roeper did to you.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Does everyone know what happened to me?!?&quot; Gerald replied defensively.  &quot;What Roeper did to me is between him and me, and a few sentences on a report doesn't come close to describing what it felt like to have electricity pumped through my body every time I refused to answer a question, unable to do anything about it, considering how much more I could take before I finally gave in and told him everything.&quot;  Gerald closed his eyes and remembered back when he was strapped down in the metal chair with electrodes stuck onto his chest.  The pain of each shock fired through his mind as clear as glass.  &quot;I would've told him everything&quot; he meekly admitted. &quot;It wasn't a matter of if, but when.  It hurt so much.  Cathy saved me from that and I'll always be grateful to her.&quot;<br />
<br />
A tear came to Gerald's eye, but he was surprised that it was a tear of happiness, remembering the moment Cathy found him.  &quot;I heard a gunshot and the 5th column officer stopped torturing me for a bit, and when Cathy... I mean Nightprowl opened the door to the interrogation room I thought she was a goner. This guy teed up and swung a pipe at her like a baseball bat right as she opened the door.  But she was like lightning - I'd never seen anyone move so fast, and she dodged the attack and stood up to him, fighting him toe-to-toe.  She was fearless.  I mean this guy was a seven foot tall monster with muscles upon muscles.  And you know how tall Cathy is, she's gotta be around five foot seven at best, and lean for her size. He towered over her, but she was hurting him - I mean she was really taking big chunks of hurt out on this guy, and while she taught her martial arts classes it wasn't like she was an experienced street fighter or anything.&quot;  Gerald omitted the concern he had when the 5th column officer was standing over a broken and bleeding Nightprowl - everything had turned out alright in the end, so her bravery outshone her mistakes.  &quot;It was amazing.  <i><b>She</b></i> was amazing.&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
***6***<br />
<br />
<br />
They both entered Zigursky prison, Jack complained about having to leave his sword at the check-in desk but did so with reluctance, and the prison warden led them to the interview room.  Samuel Roeper sat patiently and gazed straight ahead at himself in the interview room mirror, hands cuffed in front, leg irons securing his ankles.  The smug look on his face hinted that he knew why he was here, and he wondered how far he would be able to push before Gerald snapped.  It had been over five months since Nightprowl had arrested Roeper and life in prison was uninteresting at best.  He wanted to have some fun, and pushing Gerald's buttons was going to be fun.<br />
<br />
Jack entered first with Gerald following behind.  Gerald glanced up at the surveillance camera and for the first time that day he used his mutant powers, squeezing its internals until the red light flickered and died.  This wasn't an interview he wanted recorded.  He sat down opposite Roeper and looked him in the eye. <br />
<br />
Roeper smiled a big, insincere smile and started the conversation first.  &quot;How are you doing Gerry?  Nice to see you again.  You look like you've lost a bit of weight, congratulations.  Who's your friend? Is he going to make me 'walk the plank'?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;He's just here to observe; this interview is between you and me.  I'm not here for small talk, I want to know where Cathy is.&quot; Gerald probed Roeper's mind lightly, hoping that Sam would slip up and a name would spring to the forefront.  All he got was <i>'Your powers won't work on me, Gerry.'</i><br />
<br />
Sam knew what Gerald was trying to do and replied to his probe.  &quot;My mind has been conditioned to prevent the likes of you from reading me.  I spent years employed at GIFT without them knowing who I really was and you think that you can simply walk in here and get a name from me in seconds?  It won't be that easy, Gerry.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Where is she, Sam?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Gerry, Gerry, Gerry.  Even if I did know who had her I couldn't tell you; the 5th Column would kill me if they found out. If word got out that I'd rolled over on one of their customers and they let me live, their blackmailing, kidnapping, and extortion businesses would go through the floor!&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You've been on the inside for a while, Sam.  The 5th Column isn't as powerful as they once were - they've got their own internal struggles to deal with.  You must be hearing the whispers of change through your fellow inmates.&quot;  Roeper's look told him that he had heard the rumours but he didn't want to believe them.<br />
<br />
&quot;Where is she?&quot; Gerald repeated<br />
<br />
Roeper changed tactics in an attempt to shrug off the questioning. &quot;Why she's 'The Daring Nightprowl'! I'm sure she can handle herself just fine.  Besides, why would you think I know anything about her going missing?  I've been locked up the entire time.  I honestly didn't have anything to do with her abduction this time.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;We think the person who has her now is the same person who commissioned you to kidnap her five months ago.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Oh, I don't know about that.  Maybe while she was out playing hero she just got a little too curious about something&quot; Roeper replied in a low, steady voice.  &quot;I mean, you know what they say about curiosity and the cat.&quot;  Roeper studied Gerald's response, hoping for an outburst.  He knew he was starting to push Gerald's buttons and was enjoying it.<br />
<br />
Gerald couldn't help but recite the phrase in his head; <i>'Curiosity killed the cat.'</i>.  He could feel himself unravelling at the thought.  Threats to himself would fall on deaf ears, could be shrugged aside, but threats to Cathy were another matter altogether. They could not and would not be dismissed.<br />
<br />
&quot;Shuttup&quot; Gerald blankly stated, only confirming to Roeper that he'd hit a nerve.<br />
<br />
&quot;Ah, Gerry's smitten with his pet cat.  Have you told her?&quot;  Their eyes locked and Gerald couldn't hide the truth.  Roeper smiled and announced what Gerald had told him only through his looks. &quot;She doesn't know you've been pining over her for years.  Now everything is making sense.  Why you were so interested in keeping the assignment at The Nightprowler.  Why you passed up two promotions.  Why you didn't take my job which should've been yours for the taking after I was caught.  I was so <b>stupid</b>...&quot; he rocked back in his chair, glancing at the drab ceiling then focusing back to Gerald. &quot;I could've gotten all the information I needed from you if I'd just tortured <b>her</b> instead of you.&quot;  Gerald's eyes flared with rage. &quot;Ah, hindsight is 20/20&quot; Roeper added, and with an evil smile he finished his thought aloud. &quot;Maybe next time.&quot;<br />
<br />
That's when Gerald snapped. &quot;Jack, I need coffee.  Could you get me some coffee.&quot; He stated it in an eerily flat tone.  Jack looked at Gerald, who's eyes were locked on Roeper.  He knew that look, he'd seen it a thousand times.  He'd seen it on the decks of merchant ships being overrun by pirates.  He'd seen it in a countless number of taverns on both sides of the Atlantic, usually seconds before a brawl broke out. The look of a man pushed too far.  He looked at Roeper, still grinning his idiot's grin, completely oblivious to what was about to happen.<br />
<br />
&quot;Sure.  How do you take it?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Black&quot; Gerald quickly responded, still locked on Roeper.<br />
<br />
Jack exited the interview room and addressed the prison guard standing outside the door.  &quot;Things are going to get a bit loud in there in a few seconds - don't worry about it.  We're just doing a little twist on 'Good Cop, Bad Cop'.  I like to call it 'Good Cop, Psycho Cop'.&quot;  His charismatic smile did wonders and the guard just chuckled a bit and nodded &quot;Sure thing, no worries.  I won't get in your guys' way.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Thanks, much appreciated&quot; he replied with a courteous nod, then walked back to the viewing room on the other side of the two-way mirror.<br />
<br />
Gerald stared at Roeper and Roeper grinned back at Gerald for several cold seconds until the interview room table started vibrating rapidly as if it were trying to take off.  Its sturdy bolts held it to the floor, but as Gerald leaned away from the table he grinned, and Roeper saw a trickle of blood seep from his nose.  Roeper leaned back in time to watch the table break free from the floor and hurl itself at the door, blocking anyone from entering.  Roeper looked stunned.<br />
<br />
With his mind Gerald lifted Roeper out of his chair and threw him back up high against the wall and held him there.  Soon there was banging at the interview room door, as if someone was trying to get in.  &quot;You're nuts!  Y-You can't do this!  I have rights!&quot; Roeper stammered, unsure of how far Gerald was prepared to go.  He'd already gone much farther than Roeper thought he would.  Roeper knew him as &quot;By The Book Gerry&quot;, the guy who would always do everything by the rules. Today Gerald was bending and breaking every rule in that book.<br />
<br />
Gerald looked at Roeper and without saying anything aloud his voice boomed inside Roeper's mind. &quot;Where were my rights when you were shooting electricity through my body?  Where were Cathy's rights when you were selling her to the highest bidder?  I don't care about your rights.  I care about payback, and right now I will pay you back for what you did to me and Cathy.&quot;  Gerald's eyes were slits and blood was now trickling like tears from their corners.  His face was contorted into a devil's grin.  The blood from his eyes and nose, the evil grin on his face, his pale complexion, and Gerald's willingness to unleash his full powers terrified Roeper.  Gerald's cold voice once again filled his mind. &quot;Give me a reason, Sam.  Give me a reason not to kill you because I sure as hell can't think of one.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I don't know anything!  I swear to God!  I just needed Taylor to think you went off with her for a while until I could get the secrets out of you!&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You're not helping.  I need a reason, Sam&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You were the real target, not her! I swear!  I was going to leave a note saying you two went off on a vacation together and would be back in a week!  I just used her because I never liked her in the first place!  I told my superiors and they arranged to sell her and add the payment to the 5th column coffers!&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald inhaled and exhaled fiercely through his flaring nostrils, his jaw locked close in anger, his chest rising and falling with every breath.  His voice boomed through Roeper's mind  &quot;Who was the buyer?  I want a name, Sam.  Give me a name.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;All I was told was that we got a very good price for her because the guy really wanted her!  I'm talking millions!  So you're looking for a rich guy, that's all I know!&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Not good enough.  Goodbye Sam.&quot; Pressure slowly closed around Roeper's body like a vice, squeezing relentlessly<br />
<br />
&quot;NO! NO! WAIT! WAIT!&quot;  Roeper paused, but the pressure was still increasing.  &quot;I CAN'T. THEY'LL KILL ME!&quot; Roeper pleaded, sobbing like a baby.<br />
<br />
&quot;Maybe, but they won't kill you today.&quot; Gerald responded. &quot;I will&quot; he added, and a cold chill ran down Roeper's spine.<br />
<br />
Gerald kept squeezing, building up the pressure to an intolerable level.  Roeper was convinced the only way to save his life was to give Gerald the name.  &quot;Monroe&quot; he whispered between sobbing fits.  &quot;Charles Monroe.  Please.... don't kill me!&quot;.  The smell of urine filled the room and Samuel Roeper slumped to the floor in a pathetic mess, oblivious to the loud crash as the interview room table dropped to the ground in front of the door.<br />
<br />
Gerald slowly walked over to Roeper, knelt down beside him, and whispered into his ear.  &quot;Remember today, Sam.  Remember it.  If you interfere in my life or Cathy's life ever again, I'll end you.  That's my promise to you, Sam.  Remember it for as long as you live.&quot;<br />
<br />
  <br />
***7***<br />
<br />
<br />
Jack approached Gerald as he left the interview room. &quot;Whoa, Cathy told me you had some powers, but she didn't say that you could do that! I'm impressed.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald said nothing, he was still fuming from the confrontation.  Without thinking he used his sleeve to wipe the blood from his nose and eyes, then got annoyed at himself for ruining a perfectly good shirt.  He hated using his powers in anger - he always bled like that.  &quot;I guess I should expect a lawsuit. I took care of the camera but I shouldn't have damaged the table.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You didn't exactly say anything incriminating in there, Gerr.  All they have is the audio and he just started blurting things out. I think your powers allowed you to slip through a legal loophole - I know they can't count on me to confirm what happened.  By the way, did you like the banging on the door, as if we were trying to get in?  I figured it'd be a nice touch.  You were so convincing - I almost thought you were going to kill him.&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack looked at Gerald's tired and weary face, drained from the confrontation. &quot;Yeah&quot; Gerald replied.  &quot;Almost.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald phoned GIFT headquarters, Getting in touch with Carla, the resident information guru.  Anything you needed to know about anyone, you went to Carla - she was the best.  &quot;Carla, I've got a name I need you to run.  I need to know everything I can about a 'Charles Monroe'.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Sure Doctor G. I'll get right on it.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Carla, I'm not a doctor.  Please call me Gerry.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You can't fool me Doctor G; I snooped through your personnel file.  You have a doctorate so you <i>are</i> a doctor! Besides, I like how 'Doctor G' sounds.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald didn't want to argue the point any further.  His degree was earned, but it was through selfish motives.  He wanted to better understand himself and his powers so he studied all he could about the human brain and its inner workings.  Years of study got him a doctorate but no closer to learning how his powers worked. Disillusioned, he abandoned his efforts. &quot;Fine, you caught me. Even though I'm not practising, I am a doctor.  Just get me the info on Charles Monroe - it's very important.  Supposedly he's rich so he probably owns a business or two in Paragon City.  I need to know what and where they are.&quot;<br />
<br />
As they left the prison, Jack looked at Gerald with suspicion.  &quot;You're not going to phone detective whatshisname, the guy heading up Cathy's case?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;No.  Not yet.  I want to give us a head start before I tell him the name.  I'm going to get the bastard who took Cathy and I don't want anyone screwing it up.&quot; They went back to Gerald's hotel room and Jack noted the same things that the detective noted the day before - a crease in the wall, empty beer bottles, pizza on the dresser.  Jack picked up a slice and took a bite - a bit stale, but not bad.  &quot;Got any <i>cold</i> beer?'<br />
<br />
&quot;In the fridge&quot; he replied, scanning the floor for a relatively clean shirt.<br />
<br />
Jack opened the small fridge and pulled out a beer.  Twisting off the cap he said &quot;Can't you phone down for room service to get a <i>new</i> shirt?  Expensive hotels like this do that sort of thing, don't they?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I don't need a new shirt&quot; Gerald replied.<br />
<br />
Jack shook his head and wondered if he should tell Gerald what he was thinking.  Yeah, for Cathy's sake he should.  &quot;Gerr, you look like you've slept in your clothes for the past few days, and I'm guessing you probably have.  Do you want Cathy to see you so... unkempt?&quot; <br />
<br />
Gerald looked up at Jack as if he'd just been slapped in the face. <br />
<br />
&quot;Go take a shower, man.&quot; Jack continued. &quot;We've got to wait on your friend anyway.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald reluctantly agreed and went to take a shower.  Jack phoned down to the front desk &quot;Hello there, this is Gerald Simms up in room 512.  Could you guys bring a couple shirts up to my room - I've got to go out and don't have time to get mine cleaned.&quot;  He picked a shirt off the floor and read the label.  &quot;15 1/2 on the neck 34/35 on the sleeve if you don't mind.  I'll be wearing some khaki pants and brown shoes, so I'll let you colour-coordinate them for me. I trust your judgement.  Just bill my room, thanks.&quot;<br />
<br />
Ten minutes later there was a knock on the door and Jack signed Gerald's name for a couple shirts, adding a generous tip.  Gerald was still in the shower when his cell phone rang. &quot;Hello?&quot; Jack answered.<br />
<br />
&quot;Hello? Who's this.&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack heard Gerald stumble out of the shower in a hurry and a bang followed by a curse. &quot;Captain Jack Scratch, at your service.  You must be Carla.  Gerry didn't tell me what an angelic voice you have - I should answer his phone more often.&quot;  From the bathroom Gerald yelled out &quot;Was that my phone?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Oh... well... thank you&quot; Carla blushed.  &quot;Where's Gerry?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;He's taking a shower.  He shan't be but a moment...&quot; Gerald limped out of the bathroom with a towel around his waist and still dripping wet.<br />
<br />
&quot;Ah, here he is. T'was a pleasure just to hear your voice&quot; replied Jack, holding out the phone to Gerald.<br />
<br />
&quot;Hello?&quot; Gerald answered, still wincing at stubbing his toe.<br />
<br />
&quot;Doctor G, it's Carla. I must say, this guy is good.  Very good.  I've never had so much trouble tracking down one person's assets.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;So you're still trying to find some information on him?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I said he was good... I'm better.  He has layers upon layers of companies and businesses.  They all appear legitimate but I guess it's just that he has so many businesses and they all work with each other that it forms one giant tangled mess.  The hard part was finding the loose threads. You're not going to believe this, but I think I narrowed your search down to one place.  It turns out that about four and a half months ago one of the companies he owns bought out the entire top floor of the same building where Cathy lives!&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You're the greatest Carla. I owe you bigtime.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Well, your friend there, Jack... is he single?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Goodbye Carla&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
***8***<br />
<br />
<br />
On the way to Cathy's place they phoned the detective and gave him the name, omitting the fact that they knew he bought out the top floor of Cathy's apartment.  They were close to finding her - they finally had a good lead and weren't about to let it slip through their grasp.  They entered Cathy's apartment and rode the elevator as high as it would go, the penthouse floor required a key, then climbed the stairwell to the top floor - locked.  Jack looked up the stairway to the roof access. &quot;Gerry, let's take a look up top first.  I think I know how they got Cathy out of here without using the lobby or parking garage.&quot;<br />
<br />
Gerald and Jack scanned the roof searching for something, anything out of the ordinary.  Gerald couldn't find anything, but Jack did.  &quot;Gerry, what's wrong with this roof?&quot; he asked<br />
<br />
Gerald scanned the roof.  &quot;Nothing.  It looks clean.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Exactly.  It looks <i>too</i> clean.  If there's one thing heroes know about, it's rooftops.  This rooftop was recently swept clean.  Why do you think someone would go through the trouble to clean up debris on the roof of a building?&quot;<br />
<br />
It finally dawned on Gerald.  &quot;To land a helicopter without worrying about the rotor wash causing damage to the engines.&quot;<br />
<br />
Now more than ever Gerald wanted to get into that penthouse suite.  He and Jack walked back down to the stairwell door to the top floor.  Gerald put his hand on the doorknob and began to concentrate, imagining the tumblers in the lock and trying to turn them with his mind.<br />
<br />
&quot;You're trying to pick the lock?&quot;  Jack inquired.  Gerald nodded, concentrating on the lock.<br />
<br />
After a few seconds Jack spoke up again.  &quot;Have you ever picked a lock before?&quot;  Gerald shook his head, still concentrating on the lock.<br />
<br />
After several more seconds Jack began getting impatient. &quot;You know, I have a set of lockpicks if you'd like me to have a crack at it.&quot;  Gerald looked at Jack, thought about it for a second, then said &quot;Sure, if you know what you're doing.&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack shook his head in amusement, then turned and drove his boot into the door, right beside the knob.  It burst open and bits of the doorknob spilled out onto the carpet. He gave Gerald a big grin and replied &quot;Well, it's more of a large boot than a lockpick set, but it's just as effective.&quot;<br />
<br />
They both entered a small room, noting that while the top floor must have originally held a hallway for several apartments, it was now a small room in which the newly broken stairwell door, the elevator, and an apartment door took up three of the four walls.  They stopped in front of the apartment door and looked at each other.  In a deadpan voice Gerald asked &quot;Do you want to try your lockpicks again?&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack grinned and fired a swift boot to the door.  It creaked, but didn't give.  One more boot and another creak, but it held fast.  Jack got angry.  &quot;Move&quot; he stated to Gerald, then he drew his sword. Gerald stepped back and Jack yelled a battle cry, swiftly slicing his broadsword through the metal door.  Another boot to the door and the parts of the door that still remained relented, swinging back into the apartment.  They both entered slowly, but within a few steps they realized they were at the right place.<br />
<br />
In the most prominent spot of the apartment the last five months of Cathy's life was methodically spread across the wall in pictures, left to right, top to bottom.  Cathy entering The Nightprowler, her left arm in a sling. Cathy teaching her martial Arts class. Nightprowl talking to Ms. Liberty in Atlas Plaza.  Nightprowl fighting gangsters in Independence Port.  Cathy, bag of groceries in hand, fumbling with her apartment keys. Nightprowl exiting Biotechnix.  Hundreds of pictures pinned neatly to the wall, all with one thing in common - Cathy.<br />
<br />
&quot;Oh my God. They've been stalking her this whole time, ever since the incident with Roeper.&quot; Gerald was stunned.  There were even pictures of him and Cathy, both just before she had moved to Paragon City and the night before she disappeared. He was stuck in a loop, looking at all these pictures and unconsciously shaking his head in disbelief.  The man who had her was completely and utterly obsessed with her. <br />
<br />
While the shrine to Cathy disturbed Jack, he didn't waiver - he needed to make sure nobody was hiding in the penthouse suite.  Wielding his sword he surveyed every room and opened every door.  No clothes in the closets and moldy pizza on the kitchen counter told him that they left in a hurry and didn't care much about the condition of the place after they left.<br />
<br />
Jack joined Gerald at the wall of photos and put his hand on Gerald's shoulder.  &quot;We've got a solid lead now.  We're going to find her.&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
***9***<br />
<br />
<br />
&quot;Carla, this is the guy.  I need to know where he is, as soon as possible.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I've already got it. All his businesses are pretty much being run without his help and he hasn't even left his estate in four years.  Rumour has it that he's become some sort of recluse, like Howard Hughes.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Where's his estate?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;It's in Belize.  Central America.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Belize. Damn, I don't like that.  He's probably got enough money to do whatever he wants down there, so long as he greases the right palms.  I need a ticket to Belize as soon as possible.&quot;  Jack tapped Gerald on his shoulder to get his attention and held up two fingers.  &quot;Make that two tickets.  Jack's coming with me.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Let me see what I can do for ya, Doctor G.  I think I might have something even better.&quot;  Before explaining Carla hung up on Gerald, making him wonder what she had in mind.  He didn't have to wait long.<br />
<br />
Ten minutes later Carla phoned back.  &quot;Get to Paragon City International Airport.  There'll be a jet waiting for you.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You chartered us a jet!?!&quot;  Gerald remarked.  Carla was impressing him more and more.<br />
<br />
&quot;We're GIFT.  This is the hub of the organization and we have a fleet of three Gulfstreams.  Two of them are at Paragon International and one is being prepped for you as we speak. You should be in Belize a few hours after takeoff, so get moving.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;You're the greatest Carla.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I know.  It's a burden, but one I'm willing to endure.  Don't forget to pack your suntan lotion and passport.&quot;<br />
<br />
The Gulfstream was taxiing into takeoff position within the hour, and soon Gerald and Jack were airborne, off to another country and hot on the trail of Cathy's abductor. Hope began to grow inside Gerald's heart, and with it the fear of what Charles Monroe may have been doing to Cathy over the past week.  In what condition will Cathy be when she's finally found?  <i>'She's a fighter.  She'll survive and I'll get her back.  If Charles Monroe has hurt her, I'll bury him.'</i><br />
<br />
High in the air and halfway to Belize, Jack was quietly sharpening his sword and Gerald was thinking about Jack.  Cathy and Jack.  <i>'Why is he helping me?  How close are Cathy and Jack?'</i>  He thought about how easily Jack got Carla interested in him, and that was just by answering his phone; he had five months to work on Cathy.  &quot;Jack, you and Cathy - how well do you know her?&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack figured this line of questioning would arise sooner or later - he had a way with women which didn't go unnoticed by those women's men. Gerald was marking his territory, telling him Cathy was off limits  <i>'Good for him.'</i> &quot;Do you mean have I been intimate with Cathy?  Have I smelled the flowery scent of her bedroom or seen the stuffed animal she keeps on a chair in the corner?&quot;  Gerald felt himself getting hot, thinking about Cathy and Jack together in her bedroom, 'intimate', as Jack put it.<br />
<br />
Jack laughed when he saw Gerry's face redden.  &quot;I'm just kidding Gerry - it's so easy to get a rise out of you.  I noticed the scent and stuffed animal when we were looking for clues to her disappearance. The only physical contact I've had with Cathy is after calling her 'Cat' one too many times.  She slapped me, though to be fair she told me she'd hit me the next time I called her Cat, so she was true to her word.  I've settled on calling her 'Kitten'.  I just think it's cute the way she furrows her brow in disapproval and changes the tone of her voice when I call her kitten.&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack turned serious for a moment &quot;You have nothing to fear from my relationship with Cathy - it's purely professional and I respect her as a fellow hero. For a lass she's one heck of a fighter, but from what you told me in front of Zigursky Prison you already knew that.  Besides, she'd talk about you too much not to know I had no chance with her.  'He's just a friend... He's not my boyfriend' she'd say, but she was talking about you too much not to know that she cares for you.  I think she was trying to convince <i>herself</i> that she wasn't falling for you just because it would complicate her life a bit.&quot;<br />
<br />
The Gulfstream touched down on a small Belize airport just before eight o'clock at night local time, and after a short barter session they had a driver willing to take them to the Monroe Estate, a three hour drive away in a remote coastal area.  Gerald was eager to get to the estate, though he wasn't sure what he was going to do when he got there.<br />
<br />
Three and a half hours later they were almost at the estate and in desperate need of a break; the pothole filled roads (when they actually used roads) and the rock laden dirt trails had taken a toll on them, shaking them without mercy.  The driver slowed to a stop and said in broken english &quot;We here&quot;.  Gerald and Jack poured themselves out of the car and Jack approached the driver side window.  In front of the driver's view he counted off five $100 bills, much more than the amount they had agreed upon at the airport.<br />
<br />
&quot;We were never here. Nunca estbamos aqu&quot; Jack sternly stated to the driver, who nodded feverishly, his eyes locked on the wad of cash.  Jack brought the wad to rest on the hilt of his broadsword. &quot;Nunca estbamos aqu&quot; He repeated.<br />
<br />
&quot;S, usted nunca estaba aqu&quot; the driver replied nodding again.  Jack handed him the money and the car sped off in haste, as if the driver didn't want to give Jack a chance to reconsider the amount of money he had just given away.<br />
<br />
Gerald wondered about Jack's reasoning.  &quot;Why did you give him so much money and why didn't you get him to stay?  We might need him to get back.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Monroe has security - they'd find him parked here and question him.  He'd give away the fact that we're here.  I gave him the money because Monroe is rich and connected; I bought his silence in giving him more money than he would've gotten by selling us out to Monroe.  Now even if he is stopped while leaving, he will make up an excuse as to why he's here.&quot;  Jack decided not to add another just as valid reason he had; the picture of the driver with his wife and three daughters wedged almost out of sight in the corner of the windshield.  He was an honest family man and they could probably use the money.  <i>'Admitting that would ruin my reputation'</i> he decided.<br />
<br />
As they were surveying the estate wall Gerald asked &quot;You've done this before, haven't you?&quot;<br />
<br />
Jack flashed his charismatic smile. &quot;Do you mean have I ever broken into a Central American mansion for a midnight rendezvous?  maybe a few times, but I never kiss and tell.&quot;<br />
<br />
They scaled the wall and looked up at the house.  This was it; they both could feel it.  Cathy was somewhere inside and they had to find her.<br />
<br />
<br />
***To Be Continued*** Edit: Episode 2 continues in Part 3, <a href="http://www.thesafehouse.org/forums/showthread.php?t=17780" target="_blank">Cat in a Gilded Cage</a></div>
